": 0.9412406086921692, "span": {"begin": 472, "end": 483}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:32447"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cys", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997429251670837, "span": {"begin": 522, "end": 525}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3551"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IKKb", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.991324782371521, "span": {"begin": 552, "end": 556}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:32447"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cys", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997078776359558, "span": {"begin": 569, "end": 572}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:9641"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IKK complex", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9799817800521851, "span": {"begin": 731, "end": 742}}], "text": "The IKK complex consists of 3 subunits: IKKa, IKKb and NEMO. Normally, this complex can activate NFkB signaling. However, in this MIE, this complex will be disturbed in such a way it can not perform that function anymore. Currently, 3 types of IKK disturbances have been described: (Gupta et al. 2010)    Adenosine triphosphate (ATP) analogues (e.g. beta-carboline, SC-839): specific IKK interaction, preference for IKK subunits(Kishore et al. 2003)  Allosteric effect on IKK complex (Burke et al. 2003)  Interaction with Cys-179 in activation loop of IKKb     List of Cys-179 interacting compounds: (Heyninck et al. 2014)   However, not many studies performed tests on compounds of interest to identify the specific mechanisms of IKK complex inhibition (Gupta et al. 2010).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:44:09 +0000 2026"}